[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 15.9: Radiation Therapy Adaptive Planning
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Pilot · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2,000-$8,000/month (training infrastructure)
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m Here's the thing about radiation therapy that most people outside oncology don't realize: the plan you make on day one is wrong by day fifteen.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m A patient gets diagnosed with a head and neck tumor. The radiation oncologist and medical physicist spend hours crafting a treatment plan. They use CT imaging to map the tumor volume. They calculate beam angles, intensities, and fractionation schedules that maximize dose to the tumor while sparing critical structures (the spinal cord, the parotid glands, the optic nerves). It's a beautiful optimization problem, and the initial solution is genuinely impressive.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m Then the patient starts treatment. Over the course of 30 to 35 daily fractions (sessions), the tumor shrinks. The patient loses weight. The anatomy shifts. The parotid glands change shape. What was a perfectly optimized plan on day one is now delivering suboptimal dose to a target that has moved and changed size, while potentially over-irradiating normal tissue that has shifted into the beam path.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m This is called anatomical adaptation, and it's one of the hardest problems in radiation oncology.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m The current standard of care handles this crudely. Most centers create one plan and run it for the entire course. Some centers do "adaptive replanning" at fixed intervals (replan at fraction 15, maybe again at fraction 25). Each replan requires a new CT scan, new contouring (a physician manually outlining the tumor and organs on every slice), and new plan optimization. It takes hours of physicist and physician time. It costs the department significant resources. And the timing is arbitrary: replanning at fraction 15 might be too late for a fast-responding tumor or too early for a slow one.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m The question that reinforcement learning can help answer: when should you replan, and how should the new plan differ from the current one? Not on a fixed schedule, but based on what's actually happening to this specific patient's anatomy and tumor response.
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m This is a sequential decision problem. At each fraction, you observe the patient's current state (imaging, dose delivered so far, tumor response). You decide whether to continue the current plan, make minor adjustments, or trigger a full replan. Each decision affects future options and outcomes. The reward is defined over the entire treatment course: maximize tumor control probability while minimizing normal tissue complication probability. Classic RL territory.
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Reinforcement Learning for Sequential Treatment Decisions
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m ### What Reinforcement Learning Actually Is
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m Reinforcement learning is a framework for learning optimal sequential decision-making. Unlike supervised learning (where you have labeled examples of correct answers), RL learns from interaction with an environment. An agent observes a state, takes an action, receives a reward, and transitions to a new state. Over many episodes, the agent learns a policy: a mapping from states to actions that maximizes cumulative reward over time.
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m The key insight that makes RL different from simple optimization: actions have consequences that unfold over time. Choosing to replan today affects what options you have tomorrow. Delivering a higher dose in early fractions constrains what you can safely deliver later. RL handles this temporal credit assignment naturally.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m ### The MDP Formulation for Radiation Therapy
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m To apply RL, you need to formalize the problem as a Markov Decision Process (MDP). Here's how that maps to radiation therapy:
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m **State (what the agent observes at each fraction):**
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m - Current fraction number (1 through 35, typically)
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m - Cumulative dose delivered to tumor volume (in Gray)
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m - Cumulative dose to each organ at risk (OAR)
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m - Tumor volume change from baseline (from imaging)
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m - Patient weight change
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m - Imaging features (CT or CBCT metrics: tumor density, shape, position)
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m - Current plan parameters (beam angles, intensities)
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m - Time since last replan
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m The state space is high-dimensional. A typical formulation might have 50 to 200 continuous features. This is where deep RL (using neural networks as function approximators) becomes necessary.
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m **Actions (what the agent can decide at each fraction):**
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m - Continue current plan (no change)
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m - Adjust beam intensities within tolerance (minor adaptation)
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m - Trigger full replan (new optimization from current anatomy)
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m - Modify fractionation (adjust remaining fraction doses)
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m The action space can be discrete (choose one of these options) or continuous (specify exact intensity adjustments). Discrete is simpler and more interpretable. Continuous gives finer control but is harder to validate.
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m **Reward (what defines "good"):**
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m This is where radiation therapy gets genuinely hard to formulate. The reward needs to capture:
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m - Tumor control probability (TCP): higher cumulative tumor dose is better, up to a point
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m - Normal tissue complication probability (NTCP): lower OAR doses are better
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m - Plan quality metrics (homogeneity, conformity)
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m - Replanning cost (each replan consumes clinical resources)
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m A typical reward function combines these:
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m reward = α × TCP_improvement - β × NTCP_increase - γ × replan_cost
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m The weights (α, β, γ) encode clinical priorities. Getting these right requires close collaboration with radiation oncologists. Different tumor sites have different priorities: for brain tumors, sparing the optic nerve might dominate; for lung tumors, sparing healthy lung tissue is paramount.
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m **Transition dynamics (how the world changes):**
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m This is the physics and biology. Tumor response to radiation follows stochastic dynamics. Patient anatomy changes are partially predictable (weight loss trends) and partially random (day-to-day positioning variation). The transition model is what makes simulation possible, and simulation is what makes offline RL training feasible.
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m ### Why This Is Hard (The Honest Version)
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m **Safety constraints are non-negotiable.** You cannot explore freely. A policy that occasionally delivers 80 Gy to the spinal cord (the tolerance is around 50 Gy) is not acceptable, even if it achieves great tumor control on average. RL must operate within hard constraints, not just optimize expected reward. In practice, this requires a two-layer safety architecture. First, during training, penalty-based reward shaping encourages the policy to avoid unsafe actions (making violations rare). Second, at inference time, a hard constraint verification layer blocks any recommendation that would risk exceeding OAR tolerances (making violations impossible to execute). Training-time penalties alone are insufficient: a neural network is a function approximator that can output any action probability, especially in out-of-distribution states. The inference-time safety check is what provides the actual guarantee. Both layers are required. Neither alone is sufficient.
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m **Offline learning is mandatory.** You cannot run online RL on patients. You cannot randomize treatment decisions to explore the action space. All learning must happen from historical treatment data (retrospective plans, outcomes, imaging) or from simulation. Offline RL has well-known challenges: distribution shift (the learned policy encounters states that weren't in the training data), overestimation bias (the Q-function is optimistic about actions that were rarely taken), and evaluation difficulty (you can't easily test a new policy without deploying it).
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m **The reward is delayed and noisy.** Treatment outcomes (local control, toxicity) are measured months or years after treatment ends. You need proxy rewards that can be computed during treatment (dose metrics, imaging response) but these are imperfect surrogates for the outcomes you actually care about.
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m **Physics constraints.** Radiation dose delivery is governed by physics. Not every plan is physically achievable. The RL agent's actions must respect deliverability constraints (machine limitations, beam geometry, dose rate limits). This means the action space is constrained in complex, state-dependent ways.
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m **Multi-objective optimization.** There's no single "best" plan. There's a Pareto frontier of tradeoffs between tumor control and normal tissue sparing. Different clinicians have different preferences along this frontier. The RL policy needs to either learn a single compromise or be conditioned on preference parameters.
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m ### Offline RL: Learning from Historical Data
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m Since online experimentation is impossible, the entire approach rests on offline RL (also called batch RL). The idea: learn a policy from a fixed dataset of historical treatment episodes without further interaction with the environment.
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m The dataset consists of historical patients who received radiation therapy. For each patient, you have:
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m - Daily imaging (CBCT or CT)
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m - The plan that was actually delivered
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m - Any replanning decisions that were made
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m - Treatment outcomes (tumor control, toxicity, survival)
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m Offline RL algorithms that work well here include:
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m - **Conservative Q-Learning (CQL):** Penalizes Q-values for out-of-distribution actions, preventing the policy from being overconfident about actions that were rarely taken in the data
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m - **Batch-Constrained Q-Learning (BCQ):** Restricts the policy to only select actions that are similar to those in the dataset
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m - **Decision Transformer:** Frames RL as sequence modeling, conditioning on desired returns to generate action sequences
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m The choice between these depends on your data volume and the degree to which you want the learned policy to deviate from historical practice.
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m ### Simulation for Data Augmentation
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m Historical data alone is often insufficient. You might have 500 patients with full imaging and outcome data. That's not enough for deep RL. Simulation bridges the gap.
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m A radiation therapy simulator models:
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m - Tumor response dynamics (linear-quadratic model for cell kill, repopulation)
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m - Anatomical deformation (biomechanical models of tissue change)
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m - Imaging noise and artifacts
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m - Dose calculation (simplified but physically plausible)
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m The simulator generates synthetic treatment episodes that augment the real data. The RL agent trains on a mix of real and simulated episodes. The risk: if the simulator is wrong (and it will be, in some ways), the learned policy may not transfer to real patients. This is the sim-to-real gap, and it's a major research challenge.
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m **Calibrating the simulator.** You calibrate by fitting simulator parameters (tumor radiosensitivity, repopulation rate, deformation model coefficients) to match observed trajectories in your historical dataset. Validation means comparing simulated treatment trajectories against real ones using distributional metrics (Wasserstein distance on tumor volume curves, KL divergence on dose accumulation distributions). If simulated and real trajectories are statistically distinguishable, your simulator needs work. Periodically re-validate against new real data; if distributional metrics exceed a threshold, trigger recalibration before retraining the policy. The most dangerous failure mode: if the simulator systematically underestimates tumor response variability, the policy will be overconfident about "continue" actions and under-recommend replanning.
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m ### Where the Field Is Now
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m Radiation therapy adaptive planning with RL is firmly in the research stage. Several academic groups have published proof-of-concept results:
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m - Retrospective studies showing that RL-derived replanning schedules would have improved outcomes compared to fixed schedules
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m - Simulation studies demonstrating that RL policies learn clinically reasonable adaptation strategies
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m - Small prospective pilot studies (single-institution, heavily supervised)
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m No RL-based adaptive planning system is in routine clinical use as of 2026. The path to clinical deployment requires:
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m 1. Large-scale retrospective validation
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m 2. Prospective clinical trials (likely with clinician override capability)
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m 3. FDA clearance (likely as a clinical decision support tool, not autonomous)
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m 4. Integration with treatment planning systems (TPS) and record-and-verify systems
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m The system splits cleanly into two phases: training (offline, periodic) and inference (daily, at the treatment machine).
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m ### Training Phase
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m [Historical Data] → [Feature Engineering] → [Simulator Calibration] → [Offline RL Training] → [Policy Validation] → [Trained Policy]
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m **Historical Data Collection:** Gather retrospective treatment records including daily imaging, delivered plans, replanning events, and outcomes. This requires integration with the treatment planning system (TPS), the record-and-verify system, and the outcomes database.
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m **Feature Engineering:** Transform raw imaging and dosimetric data into the state representation. This includes computing tumor volume changes, OAR dose accumulation, and imaging-derived features (radiomics).
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m **Simulator Calibration:** Build and calibrate a treatment simulator using the historical data. Validate that simulated trajectories are statistically similar to real ones.
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m **Offline RL Training:** Train the policy using a combination of real historical episodes and simulated episodes. Apply safety constraints during training (constrained MDP formulation).
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m **Policy Validation:** Evaluate the learned policy on held-out historical patients. Compare decisions and predicted outcomes against actual clinical decisions. Perform sensitivity analysis on reward weights.
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m ### Inference Phase (Clinical Decision Support)
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m [Daily Imaging] → [State Extraction] → [Policy Query] → [Recommendation + Explanation] → [Clinician Decision] → [Action Execution]
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m **Daily Imaging:** Before each fraction, the patient gets a cone-beam CT (CBCT) or similar imaging for positioning. This imaging also provides the anatomical information needed for state updates.
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m **State Extraction:** Compute the current state features from the latest imaging, cumulative dose records, and treatment history.
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m **Policy Query:** Pass the current state to the trained policy. Get back a recommended action (continue, adjust, replan) with associated confidence.
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m **Recommendation and Explanation:** Present the recommendation to the radiation oncologist with supporting evidence: why this action, what the expected outcome difference is, what the risk of inaction is. Explainability is critical for clinical adoption.
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m **Clinician Decision:** The physician makes the final call. The system is advisory, not autonomous. Every recommendation can be overridden.
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m **Action Execution:** If the clinician agrees, the recommended action is executed (plan continues, intensities are adjusted, or a full replan is initiated).
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for RL training.** SageMaker provides managed infrastructure for training RL agents, including support for custom environments, distributed training, and experiment tracking. The RL training workload is compute-intensive (GPU instances for deep RL) but episodic (you train periodically as new data accumulates, not continuously). SageMaker's managed training jobs handle the infrastructure lifecycle without maintaining persistent GPU clusters.
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake.** Treatment records, imaging features, trained models, and simulation outputs all need durable, versioned storage. S3 with versioning and lifecycle policies provides the foundation. Imaging data (even extracted features, not raw DICOM) can be large; S3's tiered storage keeps costs manageable.
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The training pipeline (data extraction, feature engineering, simulator calibration, RL training, validation) is a multi-step workflow with dependencies. Step Functions coordinates these steps, handles retries, and provides visibility into pipeline state.
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for state tracking.** During inference, the system needs fast lookups of patient treatment history and current state. DynamoDB provides single-digit millisecond reads for the state vector associated with each active patient. Set a TTL attribute to archive completed treatment courses to S3 (for the training pipeline) and delete from DynamoDB after a retention period (90 days post-treatment completion) to limit PHI surface area in the hot store.
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Lambda for inference.** The policy query at inference time is lightweight: pass a state vector through a neural network, get back an action recommendation. Lambda handles this with low latency and no idle cost between fractions. Note: with ~100 active patients each getting one recommendation per day, most invocations will be cold starts (1-3 seconds). This is clinically acceptable since recommendations are generated before the patient is on the treatment table, not during active beam delivery. For sub-second latency, use provisioned concurrency (1 instance, ~$15-20/month).
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring and alerting.** Track model performance metrics, recommendation acceptance rates, and safety constraint violations. Concrete drift detection: monitor the distribution of input state features (flag if KL divergence from training distribution exceeds threshold), track rolling clinician acceptance rate (alert if it drops below 50% over a 2-week window), and compare predicted vs. actual tumor volume trajectories for patients who followed recommendations (flag systematic prediction errors).
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TB
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m     subgraph Training ["Training Phase (Periodic)"]
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m         A[S3 Data Lake\nHistorical Records] --> B[SageMaker Processing\nFeature Engineering]
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m         B --> C[SageMaker Training\nSimulator Calibration]
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m         C --> D[SageMaker Training\nOffline RL Agent]
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m         D --> E[SageMaker Processing\nPolicy Validation]
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m         E --> F[S3 Model Registry\nTrained Policy]
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m         G[Step Functions] -.->|orchestrates| B
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m         G -.->|orchestrates| C
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m         G -.->|orchestrates| D
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m         G -.->|orchestrates| E
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m     end
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m     subgraph Inference ["Inference Phase (Daily per Patient)"]
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m         H[Treatment Planning System\nDaily CBCT] --> I[Lambda\nState Extraction]
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m         I --> J[DynamoDB\nPatient State History]
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m         J --> K[Lambda\nPolicy Query]
